<TextWithNodes><Node id="0"/>The <Node id="4"/>Bank of England<Node id="19"/> on <Node id="23"/>Thursday<Node id="31"/> surprised the financial markets and delighted British businesses with a <Node id="104"/>0.25 percentage<Node id="119"/> point cut in its main interest rate to <Node id="159"/>5 per cent<Node id="169"/>. Interest rates have not been lower since <Node id="212"/>early 1964<Node id="222"/>.<Node id="223"/>

<Node id="225"/>But the mood inspired by the cut was marred by the <Node id="276"/>European Central Bank<Node id="297"/>&apos;s refusal to cut rates, and by concern at the <Node id="344"/>Bank of England<Node id="359"/>&apos;s growing pessimism about the global outlook.<Node id="405"/>

<Node id="407"/>Forecasters had expected the Bank&apos;s monetary policy committee to leave rates unchanged because of fears more cuts would fuel consumer demand and threaten higher inflation.<Node id="578"/>

<Node id="580"/>But the <Node id="588"/>MPC<Node id="591"/> said the unexpected severity of the global slowdown meant rates had to fall to keep inflation on track to hit its <Node id="706"/>2.5 per cent<Node id="718"/> target in two years.<Node id="739"/>

<Node id="741"/>&quot;Monetary policy needs to balance the weaker external environment by sustaining domestic demand growth,&quot; it said. The <Node id="859"/>MPC<Node id="862"/> believes a two-speed economy of weak internationally traded sectors and strong consumer demand is better than an economy in recession.<Node id="997"/>

<Node id="999"/>Since <Node id="1005"/>last month<Node id="1015"/>&apos;s <Node id="1018"/>MPC<Node id="1021"/> meeting, which voted eight to one to leave rates unchanged, there have been few signs domestic demand is cooling. Retail sales, household borrowing and house prices have generally been strong.<Node id="1214"/>

<Node id="1216"/>But manufacturing output, especially in the technology sector, has continued to fall sharply.<Node id="1309"/>

<Node id="1311"/>In the <Node id="1318"/>second quarter<Node id="1332"/> the <Node id="1337"/>US<Node id="1339"/> economy slowed to its lowest growth rate in eight years and the German economy is believed to have contracted.<Node id="1450"/>

<Node id="1452"/>The timing of <Node id="1466"/>Thursday<Node id="1474"/>&apos;s cut may have been prompted by the <Node id="1511"/>Bank<Node id="1515"/>&apos;s latest quarterly round of economic forecasting, to be published <Node id="1582"/>next week<Node id="1591"/>.<Node id="1592"/>

<Node id="1594"/>David Walton<Node id="1606"/> of <Node id="1610"/>Goldman Sachs<Node id="1623"/> said: &quot;They have updated their forecasts and, although inflation has been disappointing recently, the <Node id="1726"/>MPC<Node id="1729"/> are confident that it will remain on target further out.&quot;<Node id="1787"/>

<Node id="1789"/>Some City analysts said the <Node id="1817"/>Bank<Node id="1821"/> was building up a potential inflationary threat for the future. <Node id="1886"/>Michael Saunders<Node id="1902"/> of <Node id="1906"/>Schroder Salomon Smith Barney<Node id="1935"/> said: &quot;This won&apos;t do anything for the global outlook but . . . it will give the housing market a push.&quot;<Node id="2039"/>

<Node id="2041"/>But other economists supported the move. <Node id="2082"/>Martin Weale<Node id="2094"/> of the <Node id="2102"/>National Institute of Economic and Social Research<Node id="2152"/> said: &quot;The world&apos;s three largest economies - the <Node id="2202"/>US<Node id="2204"/> <Node id="2205"/>Japan<Node id="2210"/> and <Node id="2215"/>Germany<Node id="2222"/> - are all very weak, and the <Node id="2252"/>Bank of England<Node id="2267"/> was right not to be distracted by the fact that some consumption indicators are buoyant.&quot;<Node id="2357"/>

<Node id="2359"/>Hopes that the international economy might soon begin to pick up were dented when, an hour after the <Node id="2460"/>MPC<Node id="2463"/>&apos;s announcement, the <Node id="2484"/>European Central Bank<Node id="2505"/> said its governing council had decided against cutting interest rates.<Node id="2576"/>

<Node id="2578"/>Ian Fletcher<Node id="2590"/> of the <Node id="2598"/>British Chambers of Commerce<Node id="2626"/> said: &quot;In terms of supporting British manufacturing, we need a more concerted effort to cut rates and revive growth, and we don&apos;t think the <Node id="2767"/>ECB<Node id="2770"/> is playing ball.&quot;<Node id="2788"/></TextWithNodes>
